Wide complete data (continuous exposure) These data are simulated based on data from the Family Life Project (FLP), a longitudinal study following 1,292 families representative of two geographic areas (three counties in North Carolina and three counties in Pennsylvania) with high rural child poverty (Vernon-Feagans et al., 2013; Burchinal et al., 2008). These data contain economic strain (ESEATA1) as a continuously distributed variable.

Source: R/data.R
sim_data_wide.rda.Rd

Wide complete data (continuous exposure) These data are simulated based on data from the Family Life Project (FLP), a longitudinal study following 1,292 families representative of two geographic areas (three counties in North Carolina and three counties in Pennsylvania) with high rural child poverty (Vernon-Feagans et al., 2013; Burchinal et al., 2008). These data contain economic strain (ESEATA1) as a continuously distributed variable.

Usage

sim_data_wide

Format

A wide data frame of 1,292 observations There are 36 measured variables.

  • "ID" person identifier

  • "WAVE" age (in months) when data were collected

  • "ESETA1" is the continuous exposure of economic strain

  • "StrDif_Tot.58" is the continuous outcome of behavioral problems

  • "InRatioCor" is the income-to-needs ratio

  • "PmEd2" is the parent's education level

  • "state" is the family's state of residence

  • "TcBlac2" is the family's race (1 = Black?, 0 = White?)

  • "bioDadInHH2" is whether the biological father lives with the family (insert coding)

  • "HomeOwnd" indicator of whether family owns home (insert coding)

  • "KFASTScr"

  • "PmBlac2" primary careigver race (insert coding)
